<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,354,302,329]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">Divergita biformis,</emphasis>
Lobban
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[460,545,303,328]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[460,545,303,328]" pageId="7" pageNumber="242" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
<figureCitation box="[552,688,302,328]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–32" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1390,1412]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-21@6.[151,1435,190,1366]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 24–32. Divergita straight species. Figs 24, 25. LM images of Divergita spp. Fig. 24. Divergita sp., Yap specimen is a possible example of D. biformis, but is from a different location (Y36) from the SEM holotype. Fig. 25. Divergita sp., Guam specimen, possibly D. decipiens, from the same location (GU52) as the holotype, but a different collection date. D. biformis has also been seen in SEM of samples from GU52, it is not possible to tell which species is shown here. Figs 26–28. Divergita biformis, sp. nov., SEM. Holotype specimen whole mount on stub 1116, Y45-5, whole valve and details of apex and center, showing narrow, linear sternum and areola pattern. Figs. 29–33. Divergita decipiens, sp. nov. SEM. Figs 29–31. Holotype specimen whole mount on stub 566, GU52R-2, external views, showing broad, lanceolate sternum. Fig. 32. Disassociated frustule from same sample, showing interior features of rimoportula (arrow) and foramina, along with external view showing that this is not Hyalosynedra. Scale bars: Figs 24–26, 29 = 10 µm, Figs 27, 28, 30–32 = 2 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425976" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425976/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">Figs. 26–28</figureCitation>
.
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="242" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[136,1458,374,1084]" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,289,374,400]" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">Diagnosis:—</emphasis>
Valves straight, lanceolate with weakly capitate apices. Striae biseriate and decussate only on the mantle, striae on valve face mostly uniseriate with quadrangular areolae; sternum linear, very narrow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="242" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[136,1458,374,1084]" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,365,446,472]" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">Description:—</emphasis>
Live cells not observed. Valves seen in LM (
<figureCitation box="[876,1007,446,473]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–32" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1390,1412]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-21@6.[151,1435,190,1366]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 24–32. Divergita straight species. Figs 24, 25. LM images of Divergita spp. Fig. 24. Divergita sp., Yap specimen is a possible example of D. biformis, but is from a different location (Y36) from the SEM holotype. Fig. 25. Divergita sp., Guam specimen, possibly D. decipiens, from the same location (GU52) as the holotype, but a different collection date. D. biformis has also been seen in SEM of samples from GU52, it is not possible to tell which species is shown here. Figs 26–28. Divergita biformis, sp. nov., SEM. Holotype specimen whole mount on stub 1116, Y45-5, whole valve and details of apex and center, showing narrow, linear sternum and areola pattern. Figs. 29–33. Divergita decipiens, sp. nov. SEM. Figs 29–31. Holotype specimen whole mount on stub 566, GU52R-2, external views, showing broad, lanceolate sternum. Fig. 32. Disassociated frustule from same sample, showing interior features of rimoportula (arrow) and foramina, along with external view showing that this is not Hyalosynedra. Scale bars: Figs 24–26, 29 = 10 µm, Figs 27, 28, 30–32 = 2 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425976" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425976/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">Figs 24, 25</figureCitation>
) were from different samples from the SEM 
<typeStatus box="[201,310,482,508]" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">holotypes</typeStatus>
and could not be identified to 
<taxonomicName box="[658,792,482,508]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Ulnariaceae" genus="Divergita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Licmophorales" pageId="7" pageNumber="242" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="divergita">
<emphasis box="[658,792,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">D. divergita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vs. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lobban" authorityYear="2021" box="[840,980,482,508]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Ulnariaceae" genus="Divergita" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Licmophorales" pageId="7" pageNumber="242" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="decipiens">
<emphasis box="[840,980,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">D. decipiens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see below). Valves straight, 76 µm long, 4 µm wide, lanceolate with weakly capitate apices (
<figureCitation box="[738,825,518,545]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–32" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1390,1412]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-21@6.[151,1435,190,1366]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 24–32. Divergita straight species. Figs 24, 25. LM images of Divergita spp. Fig. 24. Divergita sp., Yap specimen is a possible example of D. biformis, but is from a different location (Y36) from the SEM holotype. Fig. 25. Divergita sp., Guam specimen, possibly D. decipiens, from the same location (GU52) as the holotype, but a different collection date. D. biformis has also been seen in SEM of samples from GU52, it is not possible to tell which species is shown here. Figs 26–28. Divergita biformis, sp. nov., SEM. Holotype specimen whole mount on stub 1116, Y45-5, whole valve and details of apex and center, showing narrow, linear sternum and areola pattern. Figs. 29–33. Divergita decipiens, sp. nov. SEM. Figs 29–31. Holotype specimen whole mount on stub 566, GU52R-2, external views, showing broad, lanceolate sternum. Fig. 32. Disassociated frustule from same sample, showing interior features of rimoportula (arrow) and foramina, along with external view showing that this is not Hyalosynedra. Scale bars: Figs 24–26, 29 = 10 µm, Figs 27, 28, 30–32 = 2 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425976" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425976/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
). Striae 
<quantity box="[922,1024,518,544]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.858" metricValueMax="7.112" metricValueMin="6.604" pageId="7" pageNumber="242" unit="in" value="27.0" valueMax="28.0" valueMin="26.0">26–28 in</quantity>
10 µm, biseriate on the margin with triangular areolae alternating and thus forming a decussate pattern, becoming largely uniseriate on the valve face with up to four quadrate areolae (
<figureCitation box="[521,656,590,616]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–32" captionStartId="6.[136,243,1390,1412]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1366]" captionTargetId="figure-21@6.[151,1435,190,1366]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 24–32. Divergita straight species. Figs 24, 25. LM images of Divergita spp. Fig. 24. Divergita sp., Yap specimen is a possible example of D. biformis, but is from a different location (Y36) from the SEM holotype. Fig. 25. Divergita sp., Guam specimen, possibly D. decipiens, from the same location (GU52) as the holotype, but a different collection date. D. biformis has also been seen in SEM of samples from GU52, it is not possible to tell which species is shown here. Figs 26–28. Divergita biformis, sp. nov., SEM. Holotype specimen whole mount on stub 1116, Y45-5, whole valve and details of apex and center, showing narrow, linear sternum and areola pattern. Figs. 29–33. Divergita decipiens, sp. nov. SEM. Figs 29–31. Holotype specimen whole mount on stub 566, GU52R-2, external views, showing broad, lanceolate sternum. Fig. 32. Disassociated frustule from same sample, showing interior features of rimoportula (arrow) and foramina, along with external view showing that this is not Hyalosynedra. Scale bars: Figs 24–26, 29 = 10 µm, Figs 27, 28, 30–32 = 2 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425976" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425976/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="242">Figs 27, 28</figureCitation>
). Sternum linear and very narrow. A hyaline area at each apex with a rimoportula in each. Apical pore field apparently with three rows of pores and not sunken.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
